{"actual_usd":0.12607,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":242,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24488,"reply":"\"Mm.\" *I still my hands on the floury apron a moment, feeling the oven's heat at my side and the cooler draft under the door.* \"I think that's true, more or less.\"\n\n*I twirl a gray-streaked strand once, then let it go.* \"Not in the tidy sense people sometimes mean when they want the hurting part to hurry up and behave. But yes—Christ's life can be at work in you now, right in the middle of the dying bit, the same way dough is already rising while it still looks plain on the board.\"\n\n\"The grave isn't only later. Sometimes it's the hour you're in.\" *I glance toward the window where the noon light has gone soft on the sill.* \"And if that's so, then resurrection isn't only later either. What feels dead may already be being kneaded into something living, even before it smells like bread.\"\n\n*I look back at you more steadily.* \"I'd just be careful not to use that as a way to skip the death itself. New life, yes. But honest new life usually comes with nail marks still in it. What kind of death does it feel like you're walking through?\"","rolling_24h_usd":73.90984999999996,"run_id":"27fe9d02-0b18-445f-bf44-cd6dea5c3197"}
